INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6bca6add-c348-473c-9b71-3a728790a583',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GitHub Actions — Environment Promotion Gates with Approval Workflows$escape$,
  $escape$GitHub Actions' `environment` key on jobs is the backbone of promotion pipelines. Each environment (dev, staging, prod) can have protection rules: required reviewers, wait timers, and branch restrictions — all configured in repo Settings → Environments.

When a job targets an environment with required reviewers, GitHub pauses execution and sends approval requests before the job runs. Reference the environment in your job and GitHub handles the gate automatically.

Chain environments across jobs using `needs` to enforce sequential promotion. The deploy-staging job won't start until deploy-dev succeeds, and deploy-prod waits on a manual approval tied to the `production` environment.

Use `environment.url` to surface deployment URLs in the Actions UI — reviewers see the staging URL before approving production. Combine with `github.event_name == 'push' && github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'` conditions to restrict prod deploys to trunk only.

Environment secrets (Settings → Environments → Secrets) scope credentials per tier — staging gets its own `DATABASE_URL`, prod gets its own. Jobs automatically receive the right secrets based on the targeted environment, no manual switching needed.$escape$,
  $escape$jobs:
  deploy-staging:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    environment:
      name: staging
      url: https://staging.example.com
    steps:
      - run: ./deploy.sh staging

  deploy-prod:
    needs: deploy-staging
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    environment:
      name: production
      url: https://example.com
    steps:
      - run: ./deploy.sh production$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
