INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '46e97b0a-2cbe-410c-a050-28ca71a2438a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$GitHub Actions Self-Hosted Runners — When to Use Them and What You're Signing Up For$escape$,
  $escape$GitHub-hosted runners give you a clean VM per job, but they cap out at 2-core/7GB RAM and have no access to your private network. Self-hosted runners close both gaps — use them when jobs need >7GB RAM, must reach a private VPC, require a GPU, or when per-minute costs on large matrices add up fast.

Register a runner with `./config.sh --url https://github.com/ORG/REPO --token TOKEN` and target it via `runs-on: [self-hosted, linux, x64]` (or custom labels). Runner groups let you restrict access per repo or org.

The maintenance tax is real: you own OS patches, runner binary upgrades (`./run.sh` auto-updates, but only when a job fires), and ephemeral cleanup. Persistent runners leak secrets across jobs — use `--ephemeral` flag or the `actions/runner-controller` (ARC) on Kubernetes to spin up a fresh pod per job.

For security, never register a self-hosted runner on a public repo. Malicious PRs can execute arbitrary code on your machine. Always scope runners to private repos or protected environments, and run as a low-privilege service account.$escape$,
  $escape$jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: [self-hosted, linux, gpu]
    environment: production
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - name: Run GPU benchmark
        run: python train.py --device cuda
      - name: Cleanup workspace
        if: always()
        run: rm -rf $GITHUB_WORKSPACE/*$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
